Synset.ILIDefinition: a three-dimensional geometric figure with a square base and four triangular sides that connect at one point; a pyramid with a square base.
Synset.Example: The Great Pyramid of Giza is an example of a square pyramid.

Synset.Definition: a curve whose equation in Cartesian coordinates is of the form y = a cot x.
Synset.ILIDefinition: a curve whose equation in Cartesian coordinates is of the form y = a cot x.
Synset.Example: Note that the cotangent curve, like all trigonometric graphs, is periodic.

Synset.Definition: the curve resulting from the orthogonal projection of a fixed point on the tangent lines of a given curve.
Synset.ILIDefinition: the curve resulting from the orthogonal projection of a fixed point on the tangent lines of a given curve.
Synset.Example: The pedal curve of an ellipse, with its focus as pedal point, is a circle.

Synset.Definition: a curve between two points along which a body can move under gravity in a shorter time than for any other curve.
Synset.ILIDefinition: a curve between two points along which a body can move under gravity in a shorter time than for any other curve.
Synset.Example: The brachistochrone is a cycloid with a horizontal base and with its cusp at the point A.

Synset.Definition: A head line is a crease on the palm said to represent the person's mind and the way it works, including learning style, communication style, intellectualism, and thirst for knowledge.
Synset.ILIDefinition: A head line is a crease on the palm said to represent the person's mind and the way it works, including learning style, communication style, intellectualism, and thirst for knowledge.
Synset.Example: Often, the head line is joined with the life line (see below) at inception.

Synset.Definition: In microeconomic theory, a graph showing different bundles of goods between which a consumer is indifferent.
Synset.ILIDefinition: In microeconomic theory, a graph showing different bundles of goods between which a consumer is indifferent.
Synset.Example: Since every (X , Y) combination will have an indifference curve passing through it, we can add a third axis stretching upward from the bottom left corner of the figure measuring the degree to which the individual's preferences are satisfied, and visualize the infinitely many indifference curves as representing a smooth surface that rises as the consumption of commodities X and Y increase.

Synset.Definition: Any of a family of curves defined as the locus of points p, such that each p is on a line that passes through a given fixed point P and intersects a given curve, C, and the distance from p to the point of intersection with C is a specified constant (note that for nontrivial cases two such points p satisfy the criteria, and the resultant curve has two parts).
